new file mode 100644
index 00000000..dceb80fb
--- /dev/null
+++ b/packaging/aur/PKGBUILD
@@ -0,0 +1,35 @@
+# Maintainer: Ivan Kuznetsov <ivan@ikuznetsov.com>
+pkgname=hive-bin
+pkgver=0.1.0
+pkgrel=1
+pkgdesc="TUI and agent-driven CLI for orchestrating parallel coding tasks (prebuilt binary)"
+arch=('x86_64')
+url="https://github.com/ivankuznetsov/hive"
+license=('MIT')
+provides=('hive')
+conflicts=('hive')
+# The release tarball is a relocatable, self-contained app directory that
+# bundles its own Ruby, so there is intentionally no ruby dependency.
+optdepends=(
+  'git: version control operations'
+  'github-cli: PR and release workflows'
+  'jq: JSON processing'
+  'bash: launcher and helper scripts'
+)
+source=("hive-$pkgver-x86_64-linux-gnu.tar.gz::https://github.com/ivankuznetsov/hive/releases/download/v$pkgver/hive-$pkgver-x86_64-linux-gnu.tar.gz")
+# REPLACE_WITH_SHA256_AT_RELEASE: release automation fills this from SHA256SUMS.
+sha256sums=('REPLACE_WITH_SHA256_AT_RELEASE')
+
+package() {
+  # The tarball extracts to a self-contained app directory containing
+  # bin/hive (launcher), a bundled Ruby, vendor/bundle/, lib/, templates/,
+  # schemas/. Install it under /usr/lib/hive and expose the launcher on PATH.
+  install -d "$pkgdir/usr/lib/hive"
+  cp -a "$srcdir"/*/. "$pkgdir/usr/lib/hive/"
+
+  install -d "$pkgdir/usr/bin"
+  ln -s /usr/lib/hive/bin/hive "$pkgdir/usr/bin/hive"
+
+  install -Dm644 "$pkgdir/usr/lib/hive/LICENSE" \
+    "$pkgdir/usr/share/licenses/$pkgname/LICENSE"
+}
diff --git a/packaging/aur/README.md b/packaging/aur/README.md
new file mode 100644
index 00000000..6c382d91
--- /dev/null
+++ b/packaging/aur/README.md
@@ -0,0 +1,45 @@
+# AUR packaging
+
+`PKGBUILD` and `.SRCINFO` in this directory are the **source of truth** for the
+`hive-bin` AUR package. On release they are pushed to the AUR git repo for
+`hive-bin`, with each `REPLACE_WITH_SHA256_AT_RELEASE` placeholder replaced by
+the real SHA-256 from the release's `SHA256SUMS` file.
+
+## Installing
+
+With an AUR helper such as [yay](https://github.com/Jguer/yay):
+
+```sh
+yay -S hive-bin
+```
+
+## Upgrading
+
+```sh
+yay -Syu hive-bin
+```
+
+## About this package
+
+- `hive-bin` installs the **prebuilt** `x86_64-linux-gnu` release tarball. The
+  tarball is a relocatable, self-contained app directory that bundles its own
+  Ruby, so the package declares **no** `ruby` dependency.
+- It `provides=('hive')` and `conflicts=('hive')`, so it cleanly replaces any
+  source-built `hive` package.
+- The app directory installs under `/usr/lib/hive`, with the launcher symlinked
+  to `/usr/bin/hive`.
+- Runtime tools (`git`, `github-cli`, `jq`, `bash`) are declared as
+  `optdepends`, not hard dependencies.
+- The `claude` agent CLI is also a recommended runtime tool (`hive doctor
+  --deps` checks for it), but it is **not** an `optdepends` entry: it ships via
+  npm (`npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code`), not pacman, so there is no
+  Arch package to depend on. Install it separately if you want the agent-driven
+  workflows.
+
+## Keeping `.SRCINFO` in sync
+
+After editing `PKGBUILD`, regenerate `.SRCINFO`:
+
+```sh
+makepkg --printsrcinfo > .SRCINFO
+```
diff --git a/packaging/build/README.md b/packaging/build/README.md
new file mode 100644
index 00000000..c3dd98fb
--- /dev/null
+++ b/packaging/build/README.md
@@ -0,0 +1,107 @@
+# Build & release flow
+
+This directory holds the machinery that turns the `hive` source tree into
+prebuilt, self-contained release artifacts.
+
+## Artifacts
+
+The primary artifact is a **relocatable, self-contained app-directory
+tarball**, one per release target:
+
+```
+hive-<version>-<target>.tar.gz
+```
+
+`<version>` comes from `Hive::VERSION` in `lib/hive.rb` (the single source of
+truth). `<target>` is one of:
+
+| target             | tier | runner     | notes                        |
+|--------------------|------|------------|------------------------------|
+| `arm64-darwin`     | 1    | macos-14   | macOS Apple Silicon          |
+| `x86_64-linux-gnu` | 1    | ubuntu-22.04 | Linux glibc                |
+| `x86_64-darwin`    | 2    | macos-13   | macOS Intel — best-effort    |
+
+Each tarball extracts to a directory containing:
+
+```
+hive-<version>-<target>/
+  bin/hive          launcher (sets GEM_HOME/GEM_PATH/RUBYLIB, execs bundled ruby)
+  libexec/hive      copy of the repo's bin/hive (the real CLI entrypoint)
+  ruby/             bundled Ruby runtime (bin/, lib/, ...)
+  vendor/bundle/    vendored gems incl. platform-specific FFI native gems
+  lib/ templates/ schemas/   application payload
+  Gemfile Gemfile.lock       so Bundler resolves the vendored gems at runtime
+```
+
+The tarball is self-contained: **no system Ruby is required at runtime** once
+the bundled `ruby/` is present.
+
+## How a release happens
+
+1. Bump `Hive::VERSION` in `lib/hive.rb` and tag `v<version>` (e.g. `v0.1.0`).
+2. Pushing the tag triggers `.github/workflows/release.yml`:
+   - **build matrix** — one job per target on a *native* runner. Each job runs
+     `packaging/build/build-artifact.sh <target>`, then verifies the tarball on
+     a clean environment (`bin/hive --version` must print the version; a
+     non-TTY `bin/hive status --json` must not crash the runtime). The tarball
+     is uploaded as a job artifact.
+   - **release** — downloads every tarball, generates `SHA256SUMS`
+     (`sha256sum hive-*.tar.gz > SHA256SUMS`), and creates/updates the GitHub
+     Release, attaching every tarball + `SHA256SUMS` + the repo-root
+     `install.sh`.
+   - **bump-formulae** — computes the new `url`/`sha256` for the Homebrew
+     formula (`packaging/homebrew/hive.rb`) and `pkgver`/`sha256sums` for the
+     AUR `PKGBUILD` (`packaging/aur/PKGBUILD`). Currently a documented
+     placeholder that prints the exact fields to change; promote to real
+     commits/pushes once tap + AUR credentials are provisioned.
+
+The end-user install path is the one-liner in the repo-root `install.sh`:
+
+```
+curl -fsSL https://github.com/ivankuznetsov/hive/releases/download/v<version>/install.sh | bash
+```
+
+which detects OS/arch, downloads + checksum-verifies the matching tarball,
+extracts under `${XDG_DATA_HOME:-~/.local/share}/hive/<version>/`, and symlinks
+`~/.local/bin/hive`.
+
+## Building locally
+
+```bash
+packaging/build/build-artifact.sh x86_64-linux-gnu
+# -> dist/hive-<version>-x86_64-linux-gnu.tar.gz
+```
+
+Build **on the target platform** — the bundled Ruby prefix and the FFI native
+gems are host-ABI-specific. Cross-building is out of scope.
+
+## Open risks
+
+### R1 — Charm FFI native gems
+
+`bubbletea` and `lipgloss` (the TUI backend) ship **platform-specific**
+precompiled variants (see `Gemfile.lock`, e.g. `bubbletea (0.1.4-x86_64-linux-gnu)`).
+`build-artifact.sh` runs `bundle lock --add-platform <target>` so Bundler picks
+the native variant for the build host. If a precompiled variant is missing for
+a target, Bundler falls back to compiling from source, which requires a Go
+toolchain on the runner. The bundled-Ruby copy step and the Charm native
+extensions must agree on ABI — this is the main reason the build must run on a
+native runner rather than cross-compiling.
+
+### R2 — arm64-darwin precompiled gem availability
+
+The `Gemfile.lock` currently pins native variants for `x86_64-linux-gnu` (and
+generic `ruby`). Whether upstream ships `arm64-darwin` precompiled Charm gems
+is not guaranteed. If they are absent, the `macos-14` build job must be able to
+compile them from source (Go toolchain) or the tier-1 arm64-darwin artifact is
+at risk. Track upstream gem platform coverage before cutting the first release.
+
+### Portable Ruby (R1/R2 follow-on)
+
+The current runtime bundling copies the CI runner's Ruby prefix into `ruby/`.
+A truly relocatable Ruby needs a build configured with `--enable-load-relative`
+(via ruby-build) or a welded single-binary packager such as
+[tebako](https://github.com/tamatebako/tebako). Until that lands, the artifact
+is self-contained on the *same OS/arch family* (which is all `install.sh`
+requires) but is not a machine-independent binary. See the `TODO` markers in
+`build-artifact.sh`.
