@@ -0,0 +1,67 @@
+---
+title: hive uninstall
+type: command
+source: lib/hive/commands/uninstall.rb, lib/hive/install_channel.rb
+created: 2026-07-10
+updated: 2026-07-10
+tags: [command, install, uninstall, service, json]
+---
+
+**TLDR**: `hive uninstall` stops + deregisters the daemon service, removes install.sh-managed files (or prints the `brew` / `pacman` command for package-managed installs), and **ALWAYS preserves accumulated work** — the state home (`~/.local/state/hive`) and every project's `.hive-state` are never deleted. `--purge` is non-interactive and additionally drops the global registry config, but still preserves work. Agent skills are removed through the agent marketplace, not here.
+
+## Usage
+
+```
+hive uninstall [--purge] [--json]
+```
+
+## What it does
+
+1. **Deregister the service** — stops + removes the launchd/systemd-user unit if one is installed (via [[modules/service]]). Never raises on an unsupported platform.
+2. **Handle the binary by channel** (`Hive::InstallChannel.detect`):
+   - `install_sh` — hive owns its files, so it removes the `hive`/`hv` launcher symlink(s) in `~/.local/bin` and the versioned app dir under `data_home`. Guarded: when `data_home == state_home` (a `HIVE_HOME`-collapsed layout) it removes **nothing**, so work can never be lost here.
+   - `brew` / `aur` — package-manager-owned; prints the uninstall command (`brew uninstall hive` / `sudo pacman -R hive-bin`) instead of touching files.
+   - `dev` / `unknown` — leaves the binary in place.
+3. **Preserve work** — always adds `Paths.state_home` and every registered project's `.hive-state` scaffold to the `preserved` list. On an interactive run (not `--purge`) it surfaces each scaffold with the `git worktree remove <path>` command so the operator can remove them by hand.
+4. **Global config** — removed on `--purge`, or on an interactive `y`; otherwise preserved. The state home (work) is never touched here.
+5. Prints a skills hint: agent skills are removed through the agent's marketplace (e.g. `claude plugin marketplace remove hive`).
+
+`--purge` runs non-interactively: drops the global registry config + registrations + managed binary, but **still preserves work artifacts**.
+
+## Work-preservation guarantees
+
+- `~/.local/state/hive` (daemon pid, logs, tracking state) is never removed.
+- Project `.hive-state` scaffolds are worktree-backed and hold user work — always preserved (surfaced, not deleted).
+- A `HIVE_HOME`-collapsed layout (`data_home == state_home`) short-circuits binary removal entirely.
+
+## JSON envelope (`hive-uninstall.v1`)
+
+```json
+{
+  "schema": "hive-uninstall",
+  "schema_version": 1,
+  "ok": true,
+  "channel": "install_sh",
+  "purge": false,
+  "service_deregistered": true,
+  "binary_removed": true,
+  "binary_command": null,
+  "preserved": ["~/.local/state/hive", "<project>/.hive-state"],
+  "message": "hive uninstall: daemon service deregistered; removed hive files; work under ~/.local/state/hive preserved."
+}
+```
+
+`binary_removed` is true only for the `install_sh` channel; managed installs carry the `binary_command` string instead. The error payload carries `error_class` / `error_kind: "internal"` / `exit_code` (1 or 70). Contract in `schemas/hive-uninstall.v1.json`.
+
+## Exit codes
+
+| Code | Meaning |
+|------|---------|
+| 0 | success |
+| 70 | internal error |
+
+## Backlinks
+
+- [[cli]] · [[commands/update]] · [[commands/init]]
+- [[modules/service]] · [[modules/paths]] · [[modules/config]]
+- [[operating]]
