@@ -0,0 +1,57 @@
+---
+title: Hive::Paths
+type: module
+source: lib/hive/paths.rb
+created: 2026-07-10
+updated: 2026-07-10
+tags: [config, paths, xdg, install, architecture]
+---
+
+**TLDR**: `Hive::Paths` is the XDG-best-practice resolver for hive's per-user (global) files. Every directory resolves through a three-step precedence: `HIVE_HOME` override collapses everything under one dir → legacy `~/Dev/hive` if it already exists on disk → XDG base dirs (`~/.config/hive`, `~/.local/state/hive`, `~/.local/share/hive`, `~/.cache/hive`). `Hive::Config` reads its homes from here.
+
+## Resolution precedence
+
+For every directory function the order is fixed:
+
+1. **`HIVE_HOME`** (`hive_home_override`) — when set and non-empty, EVERY path collapses under this single `File.expand_path`-ed directory. This is the explicit-override escape hatch used by the test suite (`with_tmp_global_config`) and by operators who want a self-contained home. It reproduces the historical single-directory layout (`config.yml`, `.daemon.pid`, `logs/` all under one root) exactly.
+2. **Legacy `~/Dev/hive`** (`legacy_home?`) — when the directory already exists on disk (a pre-XDG install), keep using it so existing registry / daemon state isn't orphaned. Back-compat only; **never created fresh**. `legacy_home` is expanded dynamically against the live `$HOME` (not frozen at load) so tests pointing `$HOME` at a tmp dir resolve correctly.
+3. **XDG base dirs** — the default for fresh installs, honouring the `$XDG_*` env overrides.
+
+The config/state split matters **only** on a fresh XDG install with no override — with either `HIVE_HOME` or a legacy dir present, the two collapse to the same directory.
+
+## Directory functions
+
+| Function | Fresh-XDG default | Honours `$XDG_*` |
+|----------|-------------------|------------------|
+| `config_home` | `~/.config/hive` | `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME` |
+| `state_home` | `~/.local/state/hive` | `$XDG_STATE_HOME` |
+| `data_home` | `~/.local/share/hive` | `$XDG_DATA_HOME` |
+| `cache_home` | `~/.cache/hive` | `$XDG_CACHE_HOME` |
+| `bin_dir` | `~/.local/bin` | — (fixed; where install.sh drops the launcher symlink) |
+
+- `config_home` holds the global `config.yml`.
+- `state_home` holds per-user runtime/tracking state: the daemon pid, bot pid, `logs/`.
+- `data_home` holds installed shared assets (templates/, schemas/, stage prompts) for a packaged artifact.
+- `cache_home` is for regenerable cache files.
+- `bin_dir` is always `~/.local/bin` regardless of override/legacy state.
+
+## Shared-asset resolution
+
+`shared_asset(relative)` resolves a bundled file (e.g. `packaging/service/...`, `templates/`, `schemas/`) by preferring the installed copy under `data_home`, falling back to the repo-relative path so a **dev checkout keeps working without an install step**. `Hive::Service.template` and the service backends resolve their unit templates through this.
+
+## Helpers used by callers
+
+- `hive_home_override` — the expanded `HIVE_HOME`, or `nil`.
+- `legacy_home` / `legacy_home?` — the `~/Dev/hive` path and whether it exists.
+- `xdg_dir(env_var, fallback)` — `$XDG_<VAR>/hive` honouring the env override, else `<fallback>/hive`.
+
+## Consumers
+
+- [[modules/config]] — `Config.hive_home` = `Paths.state_home`, `Config.config_home` = `Paths.config_home`, `Config.global_config_path` = `<config_home>/config.yml`. `migrate_legacy_global_config!` copies a legacy `~/Dev/hive/config.yml` forward when the resolved config_home differs (copy, never delete).
+- [[modules/service]] — `Service.log_path` = `<state_home>/logs/daemon.log`; templates via `shared_asset`.
+- `Hive::InstallChannel` — the `install_sh` channel is detected by the launcher living under `data_home`.
+
